\q2 To the hand of her mistress,
\q1 So do our eyes turn
\q2 To the Lord our God,
\q1 Until He be gracious to us.
\b
\q1 \v 3 Be gracious, be gracious to us, Lord.
\q2 Scorn enough, and more, have we borne
\q1 \v 4 Yea, more than enough have we borne
\q2 Of derision from men at their ease,
\q2 Of scorn from those that are haughty.
\s Psalm CXXIV \\ A Magnificent Deliverance
\q1 \c 124 \v 1 “Had it not been the Lord who was for us”
\q2 Let Israel say
\q1 \v 2 “Had it not been the Lord who was for us
\q1 When men rose against us,
\b
\q1 \v 3 Then alive they had swallowed us up,
\q2 When their anger was kindled against us.
\q1 \v 4 Then the waters had swept us away,
\q2 And the torrent passed over us clean:
\q1 \v 5 Then most sure had passed over us clean
\q2 The wild seething waters.”
\b
\q1 \v 6 Blest be the Lord who hath suffered us not
\q2 To be torn by their teeth.
\q1 \v 7 We are like to a bird that is just escaped
\q2 From the snare of the fowler.
\b
\q1 \v 8 The snare is broken,
\q2 And we are escaped.
\q1 \v 9 Our help is the name of the Lord,
\q2 The Creator of heaven and earth.
\s Psalm CXXV \\ A Sure Defence
\q1 \c 125 \v 1 They that trust in Jehovah
\q2 Shall be as mount Zion,
\q1 That cannot be moved,
\q2 But abideth for ever.
\q1 Round Jerusalem are the mountains,
\q2 And Jehovah is round His people
\q2 From now and for evermore.
\b
\q1 For He will not suffer
\q2 The sceptre of wrong
\q1 To rest on the land
\q2 That has fallen to the righteous;
\q1 Else the righteous might put forth
\q2 Their own hand to evil.
\b
\q1 Do good, O Jehovah,
\q2 To those that be good,
\q2 And to the true-hearted.
\b
\q1 \v 5 But those who swerve
\q2 Into crooked ways
\q1 Shall Jehovah lead forth
\q2 With the workers of evil.
\b
\q3 Peace be upon Israel.
\s Psalm CXXVI \\ Sowing in Tears
\q1 \c 126 \v 1 When the Lord turned the fortunes of Zion,
\q2 Like dreamers were we.
\q1 Then was our mouth filled with laughter,
\q2 Our tongue with glad shouts;
\q1 Then among the heathen men said,
\q2 “The Lord hath dealt greatly with them.”
\q1 Yea, the Lord had dealt greatly with us,
\q2 And we were rejoicing.
\b
\q1 Turn our fortunes, O Lord,
\q2 As the streams in the south. 
\q1 They that scatter the seed in tears
\q2 Shall reap with glad shouts.
\q1 Forth they fare, with their burden of seed,
\q2 And they weep as they go.
\q1 But home, home, with glad shouts they shall come
\q2 With their arms full of sheaves.
\s Psalm CXXVII \\ The Need of Heavenly Help
\q1 \c 127 \v 1 Except the Lord build the house,
\q2 They that build it labour in vain.
\q1 Except the Lord watch the city,
\q2 The watchman waketh in vain.
\b
\q1 It is vain for you to rise early,
\q2 To sit down (to the meal) so late,
\q1 Thus eating the bread of sorrow;
\q2 For He giveth His loved ones in sleep.
\s Psalm CXXVII \\ The Blessing of Children
\q1 See! sons are a gift of the Lord,
\q2 The fruit of the womb a reward.
\q1 Like arrows, by warriors wielded,
\q2 Even so are the sons of youth.
\b
\q1 Happy the man who has filled
\q2 His quiver full of them.
\q1 He shall not be ashamed when he speaks
\q2 With enemies in the gate.
\s Psalm CXXVIII \\ The Blessings of Home
\q1 \c 128 \v 1 Happy all that fear the Lord,
\q2 Even they that walk in His ways.
\q1 Thou shalt eat what thy hands have toiled for.
\q2 Happy and prosperous thou!
\b
\q1 Like a fruitful vine shall thy wife be
\q2 In the innermost room of thy house:
\q1 Thy children, like slips of olive,
\q2 Round about thy table.
\b
\q1 See! this is the blessing
\q2 Of the man that feareth the Lord.
\q1 The Lord shall bless thee from Zion.
\q2 Thou shalt see Jerusalem nourish
\q1 All the days of thy life.
\q2 Thou shalt see thy children’s children.
\b
\q3 Peace upon Israel.
\s Psalm CXXIX \\ A Prayer for the Discomfiture of the Enemies of Zion
\q1 \c 129 \v 1 “Sore have they vexed me from youth”
\q2 Thus let Israel say
\q1 \v 2 “Sore have they vexed me from youth,
\q2 But they have not prevailed against me.
\b
\q1 \v 3 The ploughers ploughed on my back,
\q2 They made their furrows long.
\q1 \v 4 But the Lord, who is righteous, hath cut
\q2 The cords of the wicked in sunder,”
\b
\q1 \v 5 Let all who are haters of Zion
\q2 Be put to shame and defeated.
\q1 \v 6 May they be as the grass on the house-top,
\q2 Which withers before it shoots up;
\b
\q1 \v 7 Which fills not the arms of the reaper,
\q2 Nor the bosom of him that binds sheaves
\q1 \v 8 Whereof no one says as he passes,
\q2 “The blessing of God be upon you.”
\b
\q3 In the name of Jehovah we bless you.
\s Psalm CXXX \\ Out of the Depths
\q1 \c 130 \v 1 Out of the depths
\q2 I call to Thee, Lord.
\q1 \v 2 Lord, list to my voice:
\q2 Give heed with Thine ears
\q2 To my loud supplication.
\b
\q1 \v 3 If Thou shouldst mark sin, Jah,
\q2 O Lord, who could stand?
\q1 \v 4 But with Thee is forgiveness,
\q2 That Thou mayest be feared.
\b
\q1 \v 5 I wait for the Lord,
\q2 My soul waits for His word,
\q1 \v 6 My soul looks for the Lord
\q2 More than watchman for morning,
\q2 Than watchman for morning.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Israel, hope in the Lord:
\q2 With the Lord there is love
\q1 With Him plenteous redemption.
\q1 \v 8 And He redeems Israel
\q2 From all his iniquities.
\s Psalm CXXXI \\ As a Little Child
\q1 \c 131 \v 1 O Lord, my heart is not haughty,
\q2 Mine eyes are not lofty,
\q1 I walk not among great things,
\q2 Things too wonderful for me.
\b
\q1 \v 2 Yes, I have soothed and stilled my soul,
\q2 Like a weaned child on his mother’s bosom;
\q2 Like a weaned child is my soul.
\b
\q1 \v 3 O Israel, hope in the Lord
\q2 From now and for evermore.
\s Psalm CXXXII \\ The Ancient Promise to David and Zion
\q1 \c 132 \v 1 Remember, O Lord, unto David
\q2 His sufferings all
\q1 \v 2 The oath that he swore to the Lord,
\q2 And his vow to the Strong One of Jacob,
\q1 \v 3 Never to enter his tent,
\q2 Never to lie on his bed,
\q1 \v 4 Never to give his eyes sleep
\q2 Or his eyelids slumber,
\q1 \v 5 Till a place he had found for the Lord,
\q2 For the Strong One of Jacob to dwell in.
\b
\q1 \v 6 Behold, in Ephrathah we heard of it,
\q2 In the field of the forest we found it.
\q1 \v 7 We went to the place where He dwelt,
\q2 We bowed ourselves low at His footstool.
\q1 \v 8 “Arise, Lord, and enter Thy resting-place,
\q2 Thou and Thy mighty ark.
\q1 \v 9 Let Thy priests wear a garment of righteousness,
\q2 And Thy saints shout aloud for joy.
\q1 \v 10 For the sake of David Thy servant,
\q2 Do not reject Thine Anointed.”
\b
\q1 \v 11 The Lord swore an oath unto David
\q2 An oath that He will not break;
\q1 “A scion of thine
\q2 Will I set on thy throne.
\q1 \v 12 If thy sons keep my covenant
\q2 And the statutes I teach them,
\q1 Then their sons, too, for ever,
\q2 Shall sit on thy throne.”
\q1 \v 13 For the choice of the Lord is Zion;
\q2 She is the home of His heart.
\b
\q1 \v 14 “This is for ever my resting-place,
\q2 This is the home of my heart.
\q1 \v 15 I will royally bless her provision,
\q2 And give bread to her poor in abundance.
\q1 \v 16 Her priests I will clothe with salvation;
\q2 Her saints shall shout for joy.
\q1 \v 17 There will I raise up for David
\q2 A dynasty puissant. 
\q1 I have set mine Anointed a lamp
\q2 That shall never go out. 
\q1 \v 18 Robes of shame I will put on his foes,
\q2 But on his head a glittering crown.”
\s Psalm CXXXIII \\ Brothers together
\q1 \c 133 \v 1 Behold! how good and how pleasant
\q2 Is the dwelling of brethren together!
\q1 Like precious oil on the head
\q2 That ran down on the beard,
\q1 The beard of Aaron, that flowed
\q2 O’er the head of his robe:
\q1 Like the dew upon Hermon which falls
\q2 On the mountains of Zion.
\q1 For there hath the Lord ordained blessing-
\q2 Even life that is endless.
\s Psalm CXXXIV \\ An Evening Invocation
\q1 \c 134 \v 1 THE WORSHIPPERS’ GREETING
\q1 Attend! Bless the Lord,
\q2 All ye the Lord’s servants,
\q1 Who stand by night
\q2 In the house of the Lord.
\q1 Lift your hands to the holy place,
\q2 Bless ye the Lord.
\b
\q1 THE PRIESTS’ RESPONSE
\b
\q1 The Lord bless thee from Zion,
\q2 Who made heaven and earth.
\s Psalm CXXXV \\ The Divine Power as Revealed in Nature and History
\q3 \c 135 \v 1 Hallelujah.
\q1 Praise ye the name of the Lord.
\q2 Praise the Lord, ye His servants,
\q1 \v 2 That stand in the house of the Lord,
\q2 In the courts of the house of our God.
\q1 \v 3 Praise the Lord, for the Lord is good:
\q2 ‘Sing praise to His name it is pleasant.
\q1 \v 4 The Lord for Himself chose Jacob,
\q2 Israel as His own special treasure.
\b
\q1 \v 5 Yea, I know that Jehovah is great,
\q2 That our Lord is above all gods.
\q1 \v 6 All that He willeth He doeth
\q2 In the heavens and on the earth,
\q2 In the seas and in all the abysses.
\q1 \v 7 Clouds He brings up from the ends of the earth,
\q2 Lightnings He makes for the rain,
\q2 Wind He brings out of His storehouses.
\b
\q1 \v 8 The first-born of Egypt He smote,
\q2 Man and beast together.
\q1 \v 9 Signs and wonders He sent
\q2 Into thy midst, O Egypt,
\q2 Upon Pharaoh and all his servants.
\q1 \v 10 Many nations He smote,
\q2 Mighty kings He slew
\q1 \v 11 Sihon, king of the Amorites,
\q2 Og, king of Bashan,
\q2 And all the kingdoms of Canaan.
\q1 \v 12 He gave their land for possession,
\q2 Possession to Israel His people.
\b
\q1 \v 13 Thy name, O Lord, is for ever;
\q2 Thy memorial world without end.
\q1 \v 14 For the Lord secures right for His people,
\q2 And takes pity upon His servants.
\b
\q1 \v 15 The idols of heathen are silver
\q2 Made by the hands of men.
\q1 \v 16 Mouths have they, but they speak not:
\q2 Eyes have they, but they see not.
\q1 \v 17 Ears have they, but they hear not:
\q2 Nor is any breath in their mouth.
\q1 \v 18 Like them be those that make them,
\q2 And all that trust in them. 
\b
\q1 \v 19 House of Israel, bless the Lord:
\q2 House of Araon, bless the Lord.
\q1 \v 20 House of Levi, bless the Lord:
\q2 Ye that fear the Lord, bless the Lord.
\q1 \v 21 Blest be the Lord out of Zion,
\q2 Who dwelleth in Jerusalem.
\q3 Hallelujah.
\s Psalm CXXXVI \\ The Divine Love as revealed in Nature and History
\q1 \c 136 \v 1 Give thanks to the Lord for His goodness:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 Give thanks to the glorious God:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 3 Give thanks to the sovereign Lord:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\b
\q1 \v 4 To Him who alone does great wonders:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 5 Whose wisdom created the heavens:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 6 Who spread forth the earth on the waters:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 7 Who made great lights:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 8 The sun to rule over the day:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 9 Moon and stars to rule over the night:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\b
\q1 \v 10 Who smote the first-born of Egypt:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 11 And brought Israel out from their midst:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 12 With strong hand and outstretched arm:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 13 Who cut the Red Sea in pieces:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 14 And brought Israel right through the midst:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 15 And shook Pharaoh with all his host into the sea
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\b
\q1 \v 16 Who led His folk through the desert:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 17 Who smote great kings:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 18 And slew noble kings:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 19 Sihon, king of the Amorites:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 20 And Og, king of Bashan:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 21 Who gave their land for possession:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 22 Possession to Israel His servant:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\b
\q1 \v 23 Who remembered our low estate:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 24 And rescued us from our foes:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 25 Who giveth to all flesh food:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\q1 \v 26 Give thanks to the God of heaven:
\q2 For His kindness endureth for ever.
\s Psalm CXXXVII \\ By the Waters of Babylon
\q1 \c 137 \v 1 By the waters of Babylon there we sat,
\q2 And we wept at the thought of Zion.
\q1 \v 2 On the poplars therein we hung our harps.
\q2 \v 3 For there our captors called for a song:
\q1 Our despoilers bade us be merry, saying:
\q2 “Sing us one of the songs of Zion.”
\b
\q1 How can we sing the Lord’s song
\q2 In the foreigner’s land?
\q1 If I forget thee, Jerusalem,
\q2 May this hand of mine wither.
\q2 May my tongue cleave to my palate,
\q1 If I am unmindful of thee,
\q2 Or forget to exalt Jerusalem
\q2 Above my chief joy.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Remember against the Edomites, Lord,
\q2 The day of Jerusalem,
\q1 When they said, “Lay her bare, lay her bare,
\q2 Right down to her very foundation.”
\b
\q1 \v 8 O daughter of Babylon, thou spoiler,
\q2 Happy be he who shall recompense thee
\q2 For all thou hast done unto us.
\q1 \v 9 Happy be he who shall seize and dash
\q2 Thy children against the rocks.
\s Psalm CXXXVIII \\ The Constancy of the Divine Care
\q1 \c 138 \v 1 I will thank Thee, O Lord, with all my heart:
\q2 In the sight of the gods I will sing Thy praise.
\q1 And, prostrate before Thy holy temple,
\q2 Will praise Thy name for Thy constant love.
\q2 For Thy name Thou hast magnified over all.
\b
\q1 \v 3 In the day that I called, Thou madest me answer;
\q2 Thou gavest me room, and didst strengthen my soul.
\q1 \v 4 All the kings of the earth shall praise Thee, O Lord,
\q2 When they shall have heard the words Thou hast uttered;
\q1 \v 5 And they shall sing of the ways of the Lord,
\q2 And tell of the Lord’s transcendent glory.
\q1 \v 6 For, high though the Lord is, He looks on the lowly,
\q2 And strikes down the haughty from far away.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Though my way be distressful, yet Thou dost preserve me:
\q2 Thou layest Thine hand on mine angry foes,
\q2 And Thy right hand giveth me victory.
\q1 \v 8 The Lord will accomplish all that which concerns me.
\q2 Thy kindness, O Lord, endureth for ever.
\q2 O do not abandon the work of Thy hands.
\s Psalm CXXXIX \\ The Ever-Present God
\q1 \c 139 \v 1 O Lord, Thou searchest and knowest me;
\q2 When I sit, when I rise Thou knowest it,
\q1 Thou perceivest my thoughts from afar.
\b
\q1 When I walk, when I lie Thou siftest it,
\q2 Familiar with all my ways.
\q1 There is not a word on my tongue,
\q2 But see! Lord, Thou knowest it all.
\b
\q1 \v 5 Behind and before Thou besettest me,
\q2 Upon me Thou layest Thine hand.
\q1 \v 6 ‘Tis too wonderful for me to know
\q2 Too lofty I cannot attain it.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Whither shall I go from Thy spirit?
\q2 Or whither shall I flee from Thy face?
\q1 \v 8 If I climb up to heaven, Thou art there:
\q2 Or make Sheol my bed, Thou art there.
\b
\q1 \v 9 If I lift up the wings of the morning
\q2 And fly to the end of the sea,
\q1 \v 10 There also Thy hand would grasp me,
\q2 And Thy right hand take hold of me.
\b
\q1 \v 11 If I say, “Let the darkness cover me,
\q2 And night be the light about me,”
\q1 \v 12 The dark were no dark for Thee,
\q2 But night would be light as the day.
\b
\q1 \v 13 For Thou didst prepare my reins; 
\q2 In my mother’s womb Thou didst weave me.
\q1 \v 14 I give thee praise for my fashioning
\q2 So awful, so wonderful.
\q2 Thy works are wonderful.
\b
\q1 Thou knewest me right well;
\q2 \v 15 My bones were not hidden from Thee,
\q1 When I was made in secret,
\q2 And woven in the depths of the earth,
\b
\q1 \v 16 Thine eyes saw all my days:
\q2 They stood on Thy book every one
\q1 Written down, before they were fashioned,
\q2 While none of them yet was mine.
\b
\q1 \v 17 But how far, O God, beyond measure
\q2 Are Thy thoughts! how mighty their sum!
\q1 \v 18 Should I count, they are more than the sand.
\q2 When I wake, I am still with Thee.
\b
\q1 \v 19 Wilt Thou slay the wicked, O God!
\q2 And remove from me men of blood,
\q1 \v 20 Who maliciously defy Thee
\q2 And take Thy name in vain.
\b
\q1 \v 21 Do I not hate those that hate Thee, Lord?
\q2 Do I not loathe those that resist Thee?
\q1 \v 22 With perfect hatred I hate them,
\q2 I count them mine enemies.
\b
\q1 \v 23 Search me, O God, know my heart:
\q2 Try me, and know my thoughts,
\q1 \v 24 And see if guile be in me;
\q2 And lead me in the way everlasting.
\s Psalm CXL \\ A Prayer for Preservation
\q1 \c 140 \v 1 Rescue me, Lord, from the evil man;
\q2 From the man of violence guard Thou me
\q1 \v 2 From those who plot evil in their heart,
\q2 And stir up war continually:
\q1 \v 3 Who make their tongue as sharp as a serpent’s,
\q2 And under whose lips is the poison of adders,
\b
\q1 \v 4 Preserve me, O Lord, from the hands of the wicked,
\q2 From the man of violence guard Thou me
\q2 From those who are plotting to trip up my feet.
\q1 \v 5 The proud have hidden a trap for me,
\q2 Cords they have spread as a net for my feet:
\q2 Snares they have set at the side of my track.
\b
\q1 \v 6 I have said to the Lord, “My God art Thou;
\q2 Give ear, O Lord, to my loud supplication.
\q1 \v 7 O Jehovah my Lord, my Saviour mighty,
\q2 Thou didst cover my head in the day of battle.
\q1 \v 8 Grant not, O Lord, the desires of the wicked;
\q2 And what they have purposed, promote Thou not.”
\b
\q1 \v 9 Let them not lift up their heads against me.
\q2 May the mischief they prate bring themselves to destruction,
\q1 \v 10 May He rain upon them coals of fire,
\q2 May He smite them down swiftly, to rise no more,
\q1 \v 11 No place in the land may there be for the slanderer:
\q2 May the violent be hunted from sorrow to sorrow.
\b
\q1 \v 12 I know that the Lord will do right by the weak,
\q2 And will execute justice for those that are needy.
\q1 \v 13 Surely the righteous shall praise Thy name,
\q2 And they that are upright shall dwell in Thy presence.
\s Psalm CXLI \\ A Prayer for Protection from Persecutors
\q1 \c 141 \v 1 Lord, I call to Thee: hasten, to me,
\q2 Give ear to my voice, when I call unto Thee.
\q1 \v 2 Let my prayer be presented as incense before Thee,
\q2 And mine uplifted hands as the evening mealoffering.
\b
\q1 \v 3 Set, O Lord, a watch on my mouth,
\q2 Put Thou a guard on the door of my lips.
\q1 \v 4 Incline not my heart to an evil matter,
\q2 To busy myself in deeds of wickedness.
\q1 I hate such men as are workers of evil:
\q2 Never may I partake of their dainties.
\b
\q1 \v 5 A wound l or reproof from a good man in kindness
\q2 Is oil which my head shall never refuse.
\q2 In their misfortune my prayer is still with them.
\b
\q1 \v 6 Abandoned they are to the hands of their judges:
\q2 They shall learn that the word of the Lord is true.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Like stones on a country road cleft and broken
\q2 So lie our bones scattered for Death z to devour.
\q1 \v 8 But mine eyes are turned towards Thee, O Lord.
\q2 Do not pour out my life, for in Thee I take refuge.
\q1 \v 9 Keep Thou me safe from the trap they have laid for me,
\q2 Yea, from the snares of the workers of trouble.
\q1 \v 10 Into their own nets let wicked men fall;
\q2 While, as for me, I shall pass by rejoicing.
\s Psalm CXLII \\ A Prayer for Deliverance from Persecutors
\q1 \c 142 \v 1 Loudly I cry to the Lord:
\q2 To the Lord I make loud supplication,
\q1 Pouring my plaint before Him,
\q2 Telling my trouble before Him.
\b
\q1 When my spirit is faint within me,
\q2 My path is known unto Thee.
\q1 In the way I am wont to walk in,
\q2 They have hidden a trap for me.
\b
\q1 I look to the right and the left;
\q2 But not a friend have I.
\q1 No place of refuge is left me,
\q2 Not a man to care for me.
\b
\q1 So I cry unto Thee, O Lord:
\q2 I say, “My refuge art Thou,
\q2 In the land of the living my portion.”
\b
\q1 Attend to my piercing cry,
\q2 For very weak am I.
\q1 Save me from those who pursue me,
\q2 For they are too strong for me.
\b
\q1 Bring Thou me out of the dungeon,
\q2 That I may give thanks to Thy name,
\q1 For the righteous are patiently waiting
\q2 Till Thou showest Thy bounty to me.
\s Psalm CXLIII \\ A Prayer for Deliverance and Guidance
\q1 \c 143 \v 1 Hearken, O Lord, to my prayer;
\q2 Give ear to my supplication.
\q1 In Thy faithfulness give me answer,
\q2 And in Thy righteousness.
\q1 With Thy servant O enter Thou not into judgment,
\q2 For in Thy sight can no man alive be justified.
\b
\q1 \v 3 For the enemy persecutes me,
\q2 Crushing my life to the ground,
\q1 Making me dwell in the darkness,
\q2 As those that have long been dead.
\q1 \v 4 My spirit is faint within me,
\q2 My heart is bewildered within me.
\b
\q1 \v 5 I remember the days of old,
\q2 And brood over all Thou hast done,
\q1 Musing on all that Thy hands have wrought.
\q2 \v 6 I spread out my hands unto Thee:
\q1 My soul thirsteth for Thee,
\q2 Even as a weary land.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Answer me speedily, Lord,
\q2 Because my spirit is spent.
\q1 Hide not Thy face from me,
\q2 Else become I like them that go down to the pit.
\q1 \v 8 Make me hear Thy love in the morning,
\q2 For my confidence is in Thee.
\q1 Teach me the way I should go:
\q2 For to Thee I lift up my soul.
\b
\q1 \v 9 Save me, O Lord, from my foes:
\q2 For to Thee I have fled for refuge.
\q1 \v 10 Teach me to do Thy will,
\q2 For Thou Thyself art my God.
\q1 Guide me by Thy good spirit,
\q2 O Lord, on a way that is smooth.
\b
\q1 \v 11 Spare me for Thy name’s sake,
\q2 Bring me out of distress in Thy faithfulness.
\q1 \v 12 In Thy kindness extinguish mine enemies,
\q2 And all those that vex me destroy;
\q2 For I am Thy servant.
\s Psalm CXLIV \\ The Warrior’s Stay
\q1 \c 144 \v 1 Blest be the Lord my Rock,
\q2 Who teacheth my hands to war
\q2 And my fingers to fight.
\q1 \v 2 My Rock and my Fortress,
\q2 My Tower, my Deliverer,
\q1 My Shield, behind whom I take refuge,
\q2 Who lays nations low at my feet.
\b
\q1 \v 3 O Lord, what is man that Thou carest for him,
\q2 Or the son of man, that Thou thinkest of him?
\q1 \v 4 Man is like unto a breath,
\q2 His days as a shadow that passeth.
\b
\q1 \v 5 Lord, bow Thy heavens and come down:
\q2 Touch Thou the hills, that they smoke.
\q1 \v 6 Flash forth lightning and scatter them,
\q2 Thine arrows send forth and confound them.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Stretch out Thy hand from on high;
\q2 Pluck me out of the mighty waters,
\q2 Out of the hand of the aliens,
\q1 \v 8 Who speak with the mouth of falsehood,
\q2 And lift their right hand to swear lies.
\b
\q1 \v 9 O God, a new song I would sing Thee,
\q2 On a ten-stringed harp make Thee music.
\q1 \v 10 For to kings Thou givest the victory,
\q2 And David Thy servant Thou savest.
\q1 \v 11 From the cruel sword O snatch me,
\q2 Rescue me from the hand of the aliens,
\q1 Who speak with the mouth of falsehood,
\q2 And lift their right hand to swear lies.
\s Psalm CXLIV,  \\ The Prosperity of Jehovah’s People
\q1 \c 145 \v 1 May our sons in their youth
\q2 Be as plants well trained:
\q1 Our daughters like cornices
\q2 Carved as in palaces.
\b
\q1 \v 13 May our garners be bursting
\q2 With produce of all kinds.
\q1 In the fields may our sheep bear
\q2 By thousands and ten thousands.
\b
\q1 \v 14 May no misfortune
\q2 Or loss betide:
\q1 Be no cry of distress
\q2 In our broad open spaces. 
\b
\q1 \v 15 Happy the people
\q2 That fares thus well:
\q1 \v 16 And thus fares the people
\q2 Whose God is Jehovah.
\s Psalm CXLV \\ The Gracious Kingdom Everlasting
\q1 \c 146 \v 1 I will exalt thee, my God, O King:
\q2 I will bless Thy name for ever and ever.
\q1 \v 2 I will bless Thee every day:
\q2 I will praise Thy name for ever and ever.
\b
\q1 \v 3 Great is the Lord and worthy all praise,
\q2 His greatness is unsearchable.
\q1 \v 4 One age to another shall praise Thy deeds,
\q2 Declaring the mighty things Thou hast done.
\b
\q1 \v 5 Of Thy glorious majesty they shall tell,
\q2 And I will muse of Thy manifold wonders.
\q1 \v 6 Of the might of Thy terrible acts they shall speak,
\q2 And the tale of Thy great deeds I will tell.
\b
\q1 \v 7 The fame of Thine abundant goodness
\q2 And righteousness they shall pour forth in song.
\q1 \v 8 The Lord is full of grace and pity,
\q2 Patient and rich in loving-kindness.
\b
\q1 \v 9 The Lord is good to all the world,
\q2 And His pity is over all things that He made.
\q1 \v 10 All Thy works give Thee thanks, O Lord,
\q2 And Thou art blessed of those that love Thee.
\b
\q1 \v 11 They shall speak of Thy glorious kingdom,
\q2 And of Thy might shall they discourse,
\q1 \v 12 Making known unto men His mighty acts,
\q2 And the glorious majesty of His kingdom.
\b
\q1 \v 13 Thine is a kingdom that lives through all ages:
\q2 Through all generations extends Thy dominion.
\q1 The Lord is faithful in all that He promises,
\q2 Gracious is He in all that He does. 
\b
\q1 \v 14 The Lord upholdeth all that fall;
\q2 He lifteth up all that are bowed down.
\q1 \v 15 The eyes of all look in hope unto Thee,
\q2 And Thou dost give them their food in due season.
\b
\q1 \v 16 Thou Thyself dost open Thine hand,
\q2 And fill with Thy favour all things that live.
\q1 \v 17 The Lord is righteous in all His ways,
\q2 Gracious is He in all that He does.
\b
\q1 \v 18 The Lord is nigh unto all that call Him,
\q2 To all that call upon Him in truth.
\q1 \v 19 He will do the pleasure of those that fear Him;
\q2 Their cry for help He will hear and save them.
\b
\q1 \v 20 The Lord is the keeper of all that love Him,
\q2 But all the wicked will He destroy.
\q1 \v 21 My mouth shall utter the praise of the Lord,
\q2 And all flesh shall bless His holy name
\q3 World without end.
\s Psalm CXLVI \\ The Great Protector
\q1 \c 146 \v 1 Soul of mine, praise the Lord.
\q2 I will praise the Lord, while I live;
\q1 I will sing to my God, while I am.
\b
\q1 \v 3 Put not your trust in princes
\q2 Mortal men, in whom is no help.
\q1 \v 4 When their breath goes out,
\q2 They go back to the dust:
\q1 On that very day
\q2 Their purposes perish.
\q2 \v 5 Happy he whose help
\q2 Is the God of Jacob:
\q1 Whose hope is set
\q2 On the Lord his God,
\q1 \v 6 The Creator of heaven and earth,
\q2 The sea, and all that is in them.
\b
\q1 He remaineth eternally loyal.
\q2 \v 7 For the wronged He executes justice;
\q1 He giveth bread to the hungry;
\q2 The Lord releaseth the prisoners.
\q1 \v 8 The Lord giveth sight to the blind:
\q2 The Lord raiseth them that are bowed.
\q1 The Lord loveth the righteous.
\q2 \v 9 The Lord preserveth the stranger,
\q1 Upholdeth the widow and orphan,
\q2 But the wicked He leads to disaster.
\b
\q1 \v 10 The Lord shall reign for ever,
\q2 Thy God, O Zion, to all generations.
\q3 Hallelujah.
\s Psalm CXLVII \\ The Divine Love and Power as Revealed in Nature
\q3 \c 147 \v 1 Hallelujah.
\q1 It is good to sing praise to our God,
\q2 For praise is sweet and seemly.
\q1 \v 2 The Lord doth build up Jerusalem,
\q2 The outcasts of Israel He gathers.
\q1 \v 3 He healeth the broken in heart,
\q2 And bindeth up their wounds.
\q1 \v 4 He counteth the numberless stars,
\q2 He giveth names to them all.
\q1 \v 5 Great is our Lord, rich in power,
\q2 And measureless is His wisdom.
\q1 \v 6 The Lord lifteth up the down-trodden,
\q2 The wicked He brings to the ground.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Sing songs of thanks to the Lord,
\q2 And play on the lyre to our God.
\q1 \v 8 For He covers the sky with clouds,
\q2 He prepareth rain for the earth,
\q1 Maketh grass to grow on the mountains,
\q2 And herbs for the servants of man. 
\q1 \v 9 He giveth the cattle their food
\q2 The young ravens when they cry.
\q1 \v 10 His pleasure is not in the strength of the (war-) horse,
\q2 His joy is not in the (swift) feet of men;
\q1 \v 11 But the Lord hath His pleasure in them that fear Him,
\q2 In them that wait for His kindness.
\b
\q1 \v 12 Praise the Lord, then, O Jerusalem:
\q2 Sing praise to thy God, O Zion.
\q1 \v 13 For He strengthens the bars of thy gates,
\q2 And blesseth thy children within thee.
\q1 \v 14 He bringeth peace to thy borders,
\q2 And choicest of wheat in abundance.
\q1 \v 15 He sends His command to the earth:
\q2 His word runneth very swiftly.
\q1 \v 16 Snow He giveth like wool,
\q2 Frost He scatters like ashes.
\q1 \v 17 He casts forth His ice like morsels:
\q2 Who can stand before His cold?
\q1 \v 18 He sends forth His word, and melts them:
\q2 His wind blows the waters flow.
\b
\q1 \v 19 He declareth His word unto Jacob,
\q2 His statutes and judgments to Israel.
\q1 \v 20 With no other folk hath He dealt so,
\q2 Or brought to their knowledge His judgments.
\q3 Hallelujah.
\s Psalm CXLVIII \\ The Universal Chorus of Praise
\q1 \c 148 \v 1 Praise the Lord from the heavens,
\q2 Praise Him in the heights.
\q1 Praise Him, all His angels;
\q2 Praise him, all His hosts.
\b
\q1 \v 3 Praise Him, sun and moon;
\q2 Praise Him, all stars of light.
\q1 \v 4 Praise Him, ye highest heavens,
\q2 And ye waters above the heavens.
\b
\q1 \v 5 Let them praise the name of the Lord,
\q2 For at His command they were made.
\q1 \v 6 And He fixed them for ever and ever
\q2 By a law which they dare not transgress.
\b
\q1 \v 7 Praise the Lord from the earth:
\q2 Ye depths, with your monsters, all.
\q1 \v 8 Fire, hail, snow and ice,
\q2 And stormy wind doing His word.
\b
\q1 \v 9 All ye mountains and hills,
\q2 All ye fruit trees and cedars,
\q1 \v 10 All ye wild beasts and tame,
\q2 Creeping things, birds on the wing.
\b
\q1 \v 11 All ye kings and nations of earth;
\q2 All ye princes and judges of earth:
\q1 \v 12 Young men and maidens together,
\q2 Old men and striplings together.
\b
\q1 \v 13 Let them praise the name of the Lord,
\q2 For His name alone is exalted.
\q1 Over heaven and earth is His glory.
\q2 \v 14 He hath lifted His people to honour.
\q1 Wherefore this chorus of praise from His saints,
\q2 From Israel, the people who stand in His fellowship.
\q3 Hallelujah.
\s Psalm CXLIX \\ Song of Victory
\q3 \c 149 \v 1 Hallelujah.
\q1 Sing to the Lord a new song,
\q2 Sound His praise where the faithful are gathered.
\q1 \v 2 Let Israel rejoice in his Maker,
\q2 Sons of Zion exult in their King.
\q1 \v 3 Let them praise His name in the dance,
\q2 Making music with lyre and with timbrel.
\b
\q1 \v 4 For the Lord doth delight in His people,
\q2 Adorning the humble with victory.
\q1 \v 5 Let the faithful exult and extol Him
\q2 With glad ringing cries at the temple 
\q1 \v 6 High praises of God in their mouth,
\q2 And a two-edged sword in their hand:
\b
\q1 \v 7 On the heathen to execute vengeance,
\q2 And chastisement sore on the nations
\q1 \v 8 Binding their kings with chains,
\q2 And their nobles with fetters of iron:
\q1 \v 9 To execute on them the doom that is written.
\q2 For all His saints that is glory indeed.
\q3 Hallelujah.
\s Psalm CL \\ Hallelujah
\q1 \c 150 \v 1 Hallelujah.
\q1 Praise ye God in His holy place.
\q2 Praise ye Him in His firmament mighty.
\q1 Praise ye Him for His deeds of power;
\q2 Praise ye Him for His manifold greatness.
\b
\q1 Praise Him with blast of horn;
\q2 Praise Him with harp and lyre.
\q1 Praise Him with timbrel and dance;
\q2 Praise Him with strings and with pipe.
\q1 Praise Him with sounding cymbals,
\q2 Praise Him with clashing cymbals.
\q1 Let all that hath breath praise the Lord.
\q3 Hallelujah.
